name: Lisa Marie Presley
summary: Lisa Marie Presley's posthumous memoir, released after her sudden death, unveils her profound grief and trauma stemming from the loss of her father, Elvis Presley, and her son, Benjamin Keough. The memoir reveals that Presley kept Keough's body on ice at home for two months after his death, a heartbreaking act driven by her immense pain and difficulty in letting go. Presley's experiences with her father, whom she idolised, and her relationship with Michael Jackson, whom she describes as "normal," are also explored in the memoir. Other details include a tattoo Presley got to match her son's, and the celebration of her twin daughters' 16th birthday, with poignant photos shared by her sister, Riley Keough. The memoir offers intimate insights into Presley's life and struggles, leaving a lasting legacy of her resilience and the complexities of grief.

summary: Lily Ebert, an esteemed Auschwitz survivor who dedicated her life to educating about the horrors of the Holocaust, passed away at the age of 100. Ebert's family expressed their sorrow, stating that "a light that shone so brightly has today gone dark." Her passing leaves an immense void, but her legacy of resilience and the importance of learning from the past will continue to inspire generations to come.

name: Demis Hassabis
summary: British computer scientist, Demis Hassabis, has won the Nobel Prize in Chemistry alongside two other scientists for their work on developing AI systems that can predict the structures of proteins. Hassabis, a co-founder of Google DeepMind and a University of California, London (UCL) alumnus, was recognized for his contributions to the field of artificial intelligence (AI) and specifically for developing AlphaFold, a program that can accurately predict the 3D structure of proteins. This breakthrough has significant implications for drug discovery and has accelerated the development of new treatments for diseases like Alzheimer's and Parkinson's.
